    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Pitot tube works by measuring the difference between the static pressure of the surrounding air and the dynamic pressure of the air hitting the front of the tube, which is essentially a tiny, high-tech windsock that gets squished by the wind. When you fly, the air rushes into that front opening, creating a higher pressure that the instrument converts into a needle movement on your airspeed indicator. It's a bit like a goblin trying to push through a crowd; if the crowd (the air) is moving fast, the goblin gets pushed back harder, and that resistance tells you how fast you're going.\n\nIf the pitot tube gets blocked up by ice, dirt, or even a small bird, it's a huge deal because the instrument suddenly thinks the air is still, even if you're flying at 100 knots. This can make you lose your sense of speed, leading to a dangerous stall or a crash, which is why pilots always check for ice and have backup systems ready. It's like a goblin hiding behind a wall and pretending not to exist; if you don't notice the goblin is gone, you might walk right into the wall and get hurt.",
